Dow Chemical CEO Andrew Liveris to 'transition out' after DuPont merger


Comment


Updated on February  3, 2016 at 10:04 AM
Posted on February  2, 2016 at  1:30 PM












56
Gallery: A local look at Dow Chemical Co. over the years





    
        
            By Mark Tower
mtower@mlive.com





MIDLAND, MI -- The chief executive officer of Dow Chemical Co. plans to "transition out of the company" in less than two years.
Andrew N. Liveris, a 40-year veteran of the Midland-based chemical giant, on Tuesday, Feb. 2, reiterated his plans to step down when a merger with DuPont is complete, according to a company spokesperson.
Related: Dow Chemical names new president and COO: James R. Fitterling
The statement, made during a conference call to discuss the appointment of James "Jim" R. Fitterling as president and chief operating officer, was a reiteration of an announcement the CEO made when the pending merger with DuPont was announced in December, according to the spokesperson.
Liveris' departure is expected to occur 18 to 24 months following the closing of the merger, subject to regulatory and board approval, officials said.
Liveris plans to leave the company once "the spins are in place," according to a company spokesperson. That is expected in about 18 months, or the second quarter of 2017.
When the merger between Dow and DuPont was announced, Dow also announced it would fully acquire its joint venture, Bay County-based Dow Corning Corp.
The result will be a new combined company with a market capitalization of approximately $130 billion called DowDuPont.
DowDuPont subsequently will be separated into three independent, publicly-traded companies: an agriculture company with $19 billion in revenue, a material science company with $51 billion in revenue and a specialty products company with $13 billion in revenue.
Andrew N. Liveris
Related: 5 things to know about the Dow-DuPont mega merger
Liveris, who lives in Midland with his wife Paula, has served as Dow's chief executive officer for more than a decade.
He was born in Darwin, Australia, and later graduated from the University of Queensland in Brisbane with a bachelor's degree in chemical engineering. 
His four-decade career at Dow Chemical has, according to his biography on the company's website, "spanned roles in manufacturing, engineering, sales, marketing, and business and general management around the world."
Fitterling, who has worked with Dow for 32 years, previously held the positions of Vice Chairman and Chief Operating Officer.
James R. Fitterling
In his new role as president, he will continue to have executive accountability for all of Dow's businesses, excluding Dow AgroSciences. The new president and chief operating officer will continue to report to Liveris.
According to the press release from the company, Fitterling will "play a central role in helping drive the successful completion" of the proposed merger between Dow and DuPont announced in December and the "subsequent establishment of its three independent public companies."
When announcing Fitterling's appointment, Liveris expressed his confidence in Fitterling's leadership during work on the merger, which he described as "well underway" and the creation of the resulting three companies.
"Jim has been a tremendous leader for Dow for more than three decades and has spent his entire career at our great company," he said. "His appointment to the position of President is well deserved and a reflection of his abilities and commitment to our company.
"In Jim and our Chief Financial Officer Howard Ungerleider, I am pleased to have two outstanding leaders as part of the senior leadership team at Dow leading this historic transformation of our company and our industry. I look forward to working closely with both of them to bring that transformation to completion," Liveris said in a statement.

























 
 


Aerial flyover of Dow's new corporate campus in Midland
Dow Chemical Co. plans to finish work in 2017 on a new six-story building with room for 600 employees. The new building will replace the Willard H. Dow Center 2020 building and serve as the centerpiece of the company's corporate headquarters in Midland.




Dow Chemical, a Fortune 50 company with about 53,000 employees worldwide, has more than a century of history in Midland. Earlier this year, company officials announced plans to build a new six-story corporate center there.
The new 150,000-square-foot building is to replace the current 2020 Willard H. Dow Center in Midland, and will be part of the company's 150-acre corporate headquarters campus located off East Patrick Road.
Dow Chemical has more than 6,000 product families manufactured at 201 sites in 35 countries.
Last year, the company had annual sales of more than $58 billion. Earnings before interest, income taxes, depreciation and amortization, or EBITDA, was about $9 billion.
Mark Tower covers local government for MLive/The Saginaw News. Contact him at 989-284-4807, by email at mtower@mlive.com or follow him on Twitter, Facebook or Google+.



